<h1>Problem 1244 - 2019 USA TST, P2 of 6, N</h1>
<h2 class='difficulty'>Difficulty: 9</h2>
<p>Let \(\mathbb{Z}/n\mathbb{Z}\) denote the set of integers considered modulo \(n\) (hence \(\mathbb{Z}/n\mathbb{Z}\) has \(n\) elements). Find all positive integers \(n\) for which there exists a bijective function \(g: \mathbb{Z}/n\mathbb{Z} \to \mathbb{Z}/n\mathbb{Z}\), such that the \(101\) functions \[g(x),\quad g(x)+x,\quad g(x)+2x,\quad \dots,\quad g(x)+100x\] are all bijections on \(\mathbb{Z}/n\mathbb{Z}\).</p>
